column11:
  A novel approach is proposed to link the charge symmetry breaking (CSB)
nuclear interaction and the low-energy constants in quantum chromodynamics
(QCD) for the first time by matching the CSB effect in nuclear matter.
Resulting CSB interaction is applied to study the Okamoto-Nolen-Schiffer
anomaly on the energy differences of mirror nuclei by taking $ {}^{17}
\mathrm{F} $-$ {}^{17} \mathrm{O} $, $ {}^{15} \mathrm{O} $-$ {}^{15}
\mathrm{N} $, $ {}^{41} \mathrm{Sc} $-$ {}^{41} \mathrm{Ca} $, and $ {}^{39}
\mathrm{Ca} $-$ {}^{39} \mathrm{K} $ as typical examples. The magnitude and
sign of the QCD-based CSB interactions are found to resolve the anomaly
successfully within theoretical uncertainties.
